const faqs = [
  { question: "1. What is Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI)?", answer: "Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI) is a condition in which a person experiences noticeable changes in memory or thinking that are greater than expected for normal ageing but are not severe enough to significantly interfere with independent daily life. People with MCI are generally able to manage their personal care and everyday activities, although they may need extra reminders or find certain tasks more challenging than before." },
  { question: "2. Is Mild Cognitive Impairment the same as dementia?", answer: "No. Mild Cognitive Impairment and dementia are different conditions. People with MCI have mild changes in memory or thinking while remaining largely independent in their daily activities. Dementia involves more significant cognitive decline that affects memory, reasoning, communication and the ability to perform everyday tasks independently. Not everyone with MCI develops dementia." },
  { question: "3. Can Mild Cognitive Impairment improve?", answer: "Yes, in some cases. If cognitive changes are related to reversible causes such as poor sleep, depression, vitamin deficiencies, thyroid disorders or medication side effects, improvement may occur after appropriate medical care. Some individuals remain stable for many years, while others may experience gradual progression. Regular medical follow-up is important to monitor changes over time." },
  { question: "4. What are the symptoms of Mild Cognitive Impairment?", answer: "Common symptoms of MCI include forgetting recent conversations, misplacing important belongings, difficulty remembering appointments, reduced concentration, slower decision-making, trouble learning new information and mild difficulty organising complex tasks. These symptoms are usually noticeable but do not significantly interfere with independent daily living." },
  { question: "5. What causes Mild Cognitive Impairment?", answer: "There is no single cause of Mild Cognitive Impairment. Factors that may contribute include ageing, high blood pressure, diabetes, poor sleep, depression, anxiety, vitamin B12 deficiency, thyroid disorders, certain medications and other health conditions that affect brain function. A proper medical evaluation helps identify possible contributing factors." },
  { question: "6. Is Mild Cognitive Impairment a normal part of ageing?", answer: "No. Although some slowing of memory and thinking may occur with normal ageing, MCI involves cognitive changes that are greater than expected for a person's age. Because these changes may have different underlying causes, they should be evaluated by a qualified healthcare professional rather than being dismissed as a normal part of growing older." },
  { question: "7. Can Mild Cognitive Impairment progress to dementia?", answer: "Yes, some people with MCI may later develop dementia, but this does not happen to everyone. Some individuals remain stable for many years, while others improve if reversible causes are identified and managed. Because progression varies from person to person, regular medical monitoring is recommended." },
  { question: "8. How is Mild Cognitive Impairment diagnosed?", answer: "There is no single test for MCI. Diagnosis usually involves reviewing the person's medical history, discussing memory and thinking changes, evaluating daily functioning, performing cognitive assessments and identifying any medical conditions that may contribute to cognitive symptoms. Additional investigations may be recommended depending on the individual's situation." },
  { question: "9. Can poor sleep affect Mild Cognitive Impairment?", answer: "Yes. Poor sleep can affect memory, attention, concentration and mental clarity. Sleep disorders or long-term sleep deprivation may make cognitive symptoms more noticeable. Improving sleep quality is an important part of maintaining overall brain health, although persistent cognitive concerns should still be medically evaluated." },
  { question: "10. Can exercise help brain health?", answer: "Yes. Regular physical activity supports overall health and may help maintain healthy brain function. Activities such as walking, stretching, yoga and other age-appropriate exercises contribute to cardiovascular health, which plays an important role in supporting cognitive wellbeing. Exercise should be chosen according to an individual's health status and medical advice." },
  { question: "11. What foods support cognitive health?", answer: "A balanced diet that includes fruits, vegetables, whole grains, legumes, healthy fats, nuts, seeds and adequate protein supports overall health and brain function. Foods containing antioxidants, omega-3 fatty acids and essential vitamins may contribute to healthy ageing. Individual nutritional needs vary, so dietary recommendations should be personalised whenever necessary." },
  { question: "12. How does Manovaidya support seniors with Mild Cognitive Impairment?", answer: "At Manovaidya, support begins with understanding the individual rather than focusing only on cognitive symptoms. Through structured assessment, personalised guidance and the Neuro-Ayurveda Development System, we help seniors and families understand cognitive wellbeing, emotional health, lifestyle habits and behavioural changes that may influence brain health. Our goal is to support healthy ageing, independence and overall quality of life through a holistic and personalised approach." },
  { question: "13. When should families seek medical evaluation for Mild Cognitive Impairment?", answer: "Families should consider medical evaluation if an older adult develops noticeable memory or thinking changes, increasing difficulty managing daily tasks, reduced concentration, repeated forgetfulness, confusion or symptoms that gradually worsen over time. Early assessment may help identify reversible causes, distinguish MCI from other conditions and support appropriate planning and management." },
  { question: "14. Can depression cause Mild Cognitive Impairment-like symptoms?", answer: "Yes. Depression in older adults can sometimes affect memory, attention, concentration and thinking, making symptoms appear similar to Mild Cognitive Impairment. Because several medical and mental health conditions can cause comparable symptoms, professional assessment is important to determine the underlying cause." },
  { question: "15. How can seniors reduce the risk of cognitive decline?", answer: "Although cognitive changes cannot always be prevented, maintaining a healthy lifestyle may support brain health. Regular physical activity, mentally stimulating activities, quality sleep, a balanced diet, social engagement, management of chronic medical conditions and routine medical check-ups all contribute to healthy ageing and cognitive wellbeing. If memory or thinking changes develop, early medical evaluation is recommended." },
];

